{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 261 20 "What do \+
you observe?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 232 "Does the order of integration ever make any difference?  Actua
lly in definite integration sometimes it make a lot of difference when
 trying to compute \"by hand.\".  Try to compute  the following double
 integration problem by hand:   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "int(int(exp(x^2),x=y
..1),y=0..1)" "6#-%$intG6$-F$6$-%$expG6#*$%\"xG\"\"#/F,;%\"yG\"\"\"/F0
;\"\"!F1" }{TEXT -1 4 "  . " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 262 48 "What is t
he problem you incounter immediately?  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 265 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 186 "Now reverse the order of integrat
ion and compute the same integral.  (Remember you must draw the region
 of integration and choose the appropriate limits of integration in th
e new order.)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 74 "Now compute the integral in both orders with MAPLE. Inclu
de both results. " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "int(int
(exp(x^2),x=y..1),y=0..1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*&#\"
\"\"\"\"#F&-%$expG6#F&F&F&#F&F'!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "int(int(exp(x^2),y=0..x),x=0..1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*&#\"\"\"\"\"#F&-%$expG6#F&F&F&#F&F'!\"\"" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 263 20 "What do \+
you observe?" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 202 "There are lots of continuous functions which s
imply don't have a \"closed form antiderivative.\"  By this we mean th
ere are functions f(x) for which there is no formula expression in x, \+
 F(x), for which  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "d
iff(F(x),x)=f(x)" "6#/-%%diffG6$-%\"FG6#%\"xGF*-%\"fG6#F*" }{TEXT -1 
52 "  . We have already seen one such function, namely, " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "exp(x^2) " "6#-%$expG6#*$%\"xG\"\"#" }{TEXT -1 14 " ,another is \+
 " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sin(x^2)" "6#-%$sinG6#*$%\"xG\"\"#" }{TEXT -1 81 " \+
. Ask MAPLE to compute the indefinite integral of both and display the
 result.  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "int(exp(x^2),x
);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(^##!\"\"\"\"#\"\"\"%#PiG#F(F'-
%$erfG6#*&%\"xGF(^#F(F(F(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
16 "int(sin(x^2),x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,$*&#\"\"\"\"
\"#F&*(F'F%%#PiGF%-%)FresnelSG6#*(F'F%F)#!\"\"F'%\"xGF&F&F&F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 85 "Of course the Fundamental Theorem tells u
s there is a function whose derivative is   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sin(x^2)
" "6#-%$sinG6#*$%\"xG\"\"#" }{TEXT -1 13 "  ,namely    " }{XPPEDIT 18 
0 "int(sin(t^2),t=0..x)" "6#-%$intG6$-%$sinG6#*$%\"tG\"\"#/F*;\"\"!%\"
xG" }{TEXT -1 201 "  is such a function, but we would have to use some
 numerical integration technique to compute its value for particular v
alues of x.  For example use the trapezoidal rule to compute the value
 for x=5. " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "with(student):
